name: graphic paper production, 100% recycled | graphic paper, 100% recycled | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/8538/documentation

This module is an extrapolation of the European graphical recycling paper production based on confidential primary data from 9 common graphical recycling paper (weighted average) on behalf of a project funded by the Swiss Federal Office for the Environment FOEN:  The total annual production is 1"242"000 metric tons which represents about 10.4% of the annual production of the graphical recycling papers (without newspaper) in the EU (approximately 2.8% of World production).

Service starting with the input of labour, raw materials (e.g. unsorted waste paper, lime, other chemicals) and energy 

This module includes the production of recycled graphical paper - including collected but unsorted waste paper, deinking of pulp, paper production, energy production on-site, internal waste water treatment and transports of the auxiliaries to the paper mill. Not included are the infrastructure, transport of input materials since this is supposed to be included in the market activities.
category: C:Manufacturing/17:Manufacture of paper and paper products/170:Manufacture of paper and paper products/1701:Manufacture of pulp, paper and paperboard

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Data have been collected for the years 2008-2010
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: This module is an extrapolation of the European graphical recycling paper production based on the weighted average of 9 common graphical recycling paper. According to CEPI.org, the production volume corresponds to 10.4% of the European  graphical recycling paper production and approximately to 2.8% of the World paper production.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: Primary data for the production process were collected for each of the 9 recycled graphical paper.  Mass balance of paper materials and energy balance for the energy demand were done for each paper individually. The average data was then weighted according to their respective production volume
